    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-16T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-16T01:00:00-05:00" n="125"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d125">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Kulangsu/135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Amoy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVitty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Amoy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-16T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 16, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 16—10:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Japanese today withdrew all but 30 marines from Settlement. Municipal Council
                    has requested Consular Body to land naval forces and this morning we landed
                    small patrol to look over American property to be protected if necessary. It now
                    seems clear that the assassin of Ang is a member of only one of the Formosan
                    gangs and that he has taken refuge in Amoy and that the Japanese used the
                    incident as an endeavor to attempt to take over International Settlement.
                    British Admiral arrived today and Captain Stapler is consulting with him as to
                    joint action to be taken.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVitty</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
